post_text: Good evening. This is an important message for Panama School families. This afternoon, the state Board of Education voted to close all Oklahoma schools, effective immediately, until at least April 6 in an effort to minimize the spread of COVID-19. This means, following spring break, Panama School students will not return to school for at least two weeks, and possibly longer, if health officials deem it necessary. Employees will receive information about their responsibilities during the school closure over the next few days. For more information about COVID-19 and for answers to questions about the school closure, please visit our website at panama.k12.ok.us or our District Facebook page. Again, there will be no school for Panama students until at least April 6. Thank you for your flexibility and understanding. Please be safe and have a wonderful evening.

post_text:
We are so pleased with our Triple A Students (Academics, Attitude, and Academics). Their commitment to their education this past semester has been awesome. The only improvement to this group would be having more students join the ranks.

All our students are being presented a quality education. Triple A students choose to accept this opportunity to grow academically. The ultimate reward will be a better start in their educational life after high school but there is nothing wrong with receiving rewards while in school.

This week Triple A students have been enjoying a relaxing time of fun and friendship with their peers celebrating their achievement. Playing games, watching movies, and going to watch a movie in the theater have been on the list of things to do for the group. Check out the short video showing one of the fun events.

We don't know of a student in our high school that cannot achieve this goal of becoming a Triple A student. Parents please encourage and support your students. Point them towards setting this goal for the next semester.

post_text:
To: Parents of High School Juniors
FROM: Panama Public Schools
Date: 8/30/2019

Panama Public Schools is communicating with parents of students who will be juniors during the 2019-20 school year.
Our school district plans to administer the ACT® test in spring 2020 to eligible juniors as part of the state contract with the Oklahoma State Department of Education and ACT.
Last year over 95% of Oklahoma schools selected to administer the ACT. Our district believes this is an excellent opportunity for all eligible juniors to take the ACT at no cost to them or their families.
Additional information on why we chose the ACT can be found at:
https://www.act.org/content/act/en/products-and-services/the-act/scores/act-vs-sat.html
8 Reasons to Choose the ACT Test
Should you have any questions/comments, please reply by November 1st, 2019 to: janethopson@panama.k12.ok.us

Janet Hopson
Panama Public Schools District Testing Coordinator

post_text:
Parents of seniors: We are hosting a Financial Aid night for seniors and parents. CASC will be here October 3rd from 4:00-7:00 PM to help you fill out FAFSA. ITS FREE TO APPLY!!!

Important facts:

FAFSA is available October 1 each year.

Some aid is awarded on a first-come, first-served basis. It is best to apply as soon as possible after October 1.

By completing the FAFSA, you are automatically applying for Pell Grant (Free Money)

Most scholarship applications require that you complete the FAFSA.

ALL YOU NEED TO BRING WITH YOU IS:

Social Security Number

Date of divorce, marriage or widowed

Federal income tax returns, W-2’s, and other records of money earned

Record of untaxed income, such as child support, interest income and veterans non-education benefits.

Don’t let the FAFSA scare you! CASC staff provides free, hands on assistance to help you.

We hope that you will take advantage of this resource. See you October 3rd.

Panama Youth Baseball camp will be held Saturday, March 9th 2019. Grades k-6 runs from 9 to 12. The pitching and catching camp starts at 1 p.m. and runs until 3:30 p.m. Each camp cost is $25 dollars. For those wanting to complete both camps, the cost is $40 dollars.
The location for the camps is the Panama High School baseball field. Each camper gets a t-shirt. The camps are conducted by Coaches Chris Gollihare, Wes Tackett, Randy Darneal, and Richard Cheely along with high school baseball players.
All participants need to bring a glove, personal helmet, and a bat if they have one. A Concession stand is available. Registration forms and payment are due by February 27th. The Upper and Lower Elementary Offices have extra registration forms.

post_text: The Biannual Panama Alumni Banquet is scheduled for April 20th, 2019. The event will take place at the old rock gym at the corner of Goodnight and Missouri. If you want to be a part of the Alumni Banquet Committee, plan to attend our meeting this Monday evening (February 11th) starting at 6 p.m. at the old rock gym. Each year the Panama Alumni provides a $300 scholarship to two seniors ($600) whose parents have graduated from Panama. The only avenue Alumni have used to provide this scholarship has been funds received from the Biannual banquet. We have received some other donations but the most important source for reaching our goal continues to be the banquet. We hope to see lots of Alumni there this year. We invited Panama Alumni Jay Falkner, Carl Albert President, to join us this year and I am sure if his schedule permits, he will be with us. We hope to see many more alumni attend.

post_text:
Panama Elementary just completed their annual food drive. Due to their efforts, 30 families received food for their holiday meal.

Two classes at the Lower Elementary tied for bringing the most food items. The two classes collecting the most food items were Mrs. Bruce’s third grade class and Mrs. Restines’s third grade class.

The Upper Elementary class collecting the most food items was Mrs. Cagle’s 4th grade class.

Thanks to Mrs. Stephanie Diamond for heading up this project again this year and Mrs. Lynette Trout for her hard work organizing the food items as they came in. Thanks to all the others that made this event possible.

post_text: The yearbook has made arrangements to re-open online sales, but there will be no more sales after March 31. Any further delays will make it impossible for our students to have their books before school lets out for summer break. Please make sure to check with school officials when students return for Fall 2017 to order a yearbook next year. The yearbook staff always begin yearbook orders in September and closes on-campus ordering at the end of November. Online orders will always close before Spring Break. Thank you for your support and understanding.
